Wyclif, limiting God's power by His will, calls the fixed number of possible things that will be produced, infinite lo us (p. 88 to end of chapter).

Chapter V. brings us to a discussion of causal propositionS, after the writer’s usual fashion, expounding his views on causes, accidents, modes of being, the identity of God causing Man withMan caused by God, and the origin of evil.

Os such propositions there are two kinds, the one affirmative, the other negative, and each is reducible to a categorical having the same sense. A conditional proposition does not imply causation, but only a nexus between two propositions, neither does a copulative, which means nothing beyond the coexistence of the two (pp. 90, 91). Accidents are caused by their subjects: because you are a man, you have such and such qualitieS. We can only state that the word signifies ethat which produces an effect’, that of which the entity precedes the thing caused3 whilst ‘effect' is that other being produced, and of which the entity ssows from that cause. All beings are causes and effectS. Possibly there is no last being, but there is a first one; which is, according to Wyclif, not God, but Essence. This essence is that which is created (unum creatum); but it is itself neither created nor caused. In short, it seems identical with that Transcendent Being, of which we have already heard a good deal, and which is common both to God and to the creature3 a conception so closely verging upon Pantheism that Wyclif avoids that conclusion only by his surprising skill in argument, and the constant employment of the highest mysteries of the Christian faith used as points of comparison and instances to maintain the value of his subtle distinctions (p. 91, l. 39, 4o; p. 92, l. 1—18).
